<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-272-366  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 272 366.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  May 15 1989 v11 n20 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sim City could teach U.S. managers independent thinking. (Ridingthe Fourth Wave) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Angus, Jeff.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US management has been declining since 1978 because of poorthinking skills.andP;  A tool to teach problem-solving thinking, SimCity from Maxis Software, could help reverse that decline.andP;  SimCity is a brilliant, addictive piece of programming and because notwo Sim City simulations are ever the same, Sim City teachesindependent judgment skills in the face of volatile conditions.andO;The Macintosh version of Sim City offers users the chance tomanage a major urban area during a crisis, such as San Franciscoduring the 1906 earthquake.andP;  One option, building a city fromscratch, would make a good test of job applicants' problem-solvingabilities.andP;  Another option, managing a small and poor city, canindicate how well a manager can do with limited resources.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Maxis (products).andO;Product:   SimCity (computer game) (business use).andO;Topic:     Management DevelopmentProductivityComputer-Assisted InstructionEducationManagement ScienceSimulationProblem SolvingApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>